instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The twin lifecycle in the proposed framework follows four explicit phases. First, the Device Modeling stage involves building control engineers enriching a native BIM model (Level 3/4) with sensor, actuator, and controller entities (BCS components). Second, the Transformation stage applies Model‑Driven Engineering (MDE) techniques to automatically map the enriched BIM elements onto a structured semantic representation (e.g., ontology‑aligned JSON or UML models). Third, the Deployment stage generates executable DT artifacts—containerised micro‑services or runtime modules—that embody the control logic and can be instantiated on an edge or cloud platform. Finally, the Runtime Monitoring & Control stage synchronises real‑time telemetry from the physical building via bidirectional data‑exchange protocols, updates the digital twin state, and provides facility‑manager‑centric visualization interfaces. Transition between stages is governed by automated validation of BIM constraints and registration of the generated artifacts in a deployment registry, while governance is achieved through role‑based access controls for Building Control Engineers, Facility Managers, and DT Engineers."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Fidelity is maintained by tightly coupling the BIM‑derived geometric model to the twin artefacts; geometric integrity is preserved via IFC export and UE 5 rendering, while behavioral fidelity is driven by the TwinComponent/FeatureParser correspondence.  Validation occurs at multiple stages: the conversion pipeline checks metadata completeness; Ditto enforces value‑range and unit policies for sensor data; pre‑execution checks guarantee that actuator commands cannot violate safety bounds.  Fault tolerance is achieved through Eclipse Hono’s at‑least‑once delivery semantics and Ditto’s persistent event storage, ensuring resilience against network or service failures.  Continuous synchronization between physical devices and twin state, combined with the aforementioned policies and validation layers, forms the system’s quality‑assurance loop for models and data."
]
